\subsection{Discrete Euler method}
We consider the Euler-Maruyama scheme for solving numerically \eqref{eq:reference_equation}. Given a timestep $h>0$ we define a time discretization $\{t_i\}_{i=0}^{N},t_i = ih,h=T/N$. The numerical solution $X_h(t)$ is defined as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete_EM}
	\begin{cases}
		X_h^d(t_{i+1}) = -A(X_h^d(t_i)-\mu)h + \sigma (W(t_{i+1}) - W(t_{i})), \quad A\in \mathbb{R}^{2\times 2}, \\
		X_h^d(0) = X_0, \quad X_0 \in D.
	\end{cases}
\end{equation} 
We then extract with a Montecarlo simulation the following quantities 
\begin{align}\label{eq:estimates_DEM}
\begin{split}
	\tau_h^d &= \min \{T,\hat\tau_h^d \}, \quad \hat\tau_h^d = \min\{t_i = hi, i = 1,\dots, N \colon X_h(t_i) \notin D\}, \\
	\phi_h^d &= \mathbbm{1}_{\hat\tau_h^d < T}.
\end{split}
\end{align}
We perform a Montecarlo simulation on the exact solution on a smaller timestep $h_{ex}$ in order to obtain an accurate estimate of the quantities
\begin{align}\label{eq:estimates_exact}
\begin{split}
	\tau &= \min \{T,\hat\tau \}, \quad \hat\tau = \min\{t \colon X(t) \notin D\}, \\
	\phi &= \mathbbm{1}_{\hat\tau < T}.
\end{split}
\end{align}
Finally, we compare the numerical values obtained in \eqref{eq:estimates_DEM} and \eqref{eq:estimates_exact} to obtain the following error estimations
\begin{align}\label{eq:error_DEM}
\begin{split}
	err_h^{\tau,d} &= | \tau_h^d - \tau |, \\
	err_h^{\phi,d} &= | \phi_h^d - \phi |.
\end{split}
\end{align}
It has been proved \cite{Gobet2001} that the error is $O(h^{1/2})$. 

